\section{Maxwell\rq s Equations in Three Dimensions}\label{Maxwells_equations}
The differential form of Maxwell\rq s equations and constitutive relations \cite{Taflove_book_00} can be written as:\index{Maxwell\rq s equations}\\
%\begin{itemize}%{enumerate}%[a.]
%\item
	Faraday\rq s law:
\begin{eqnarray}\label{Faraday_eqn}
\bigtriangledown\times \overrightarrow{E}=-\frac{\partial \overrightarrow{B}}{\partial t}-\sigma_m\overrightarrow{H}-\overrightarrow{M}
\end{eqnarray}
%\item
	Ampere\rq s Law:
\begin{eqnarray}\label{Ampere_eqn}
\bigtriangledown\times \overrightarrow{H}=\frac{\partial \overrightarrow{D}}{\partial t}+\sigma_e\overrightarrow{E}+\overrightarrow{J}
\end{eqnarray}
%\item
	Gauss\rq s Law for the electric field:
	\begin{eqnarray}\label{Gauses_ef_eqn}
\bigtriangledown\cdot \overrightarrow{D}=\rho_e
\end{eqnarray}
%\item
	Gauss\rq s Law for the magnetic field:
	\begin{eqnarray}\label{Gauses_mf_eqn}
\bigtriangledown\cdot \overrightarrow{B}=\rho_m
\end{eqnarray}
%\item
	Constitutive relations:
\begin{subequations}
\begin{eqnarray}\label{Consti_rela}
\overrightarrow{B}=\mu\overrightarrow{H} \label{Consti_rela_BH}\\
\overrightarrow{D}=\varepsilon\overrightarrow{E} \label{Consti_rela_DE}
\end{eqnarray}
\end{subequations}
