In case of electromagnetic phenomenon in free space, or more general, in a perfect dielectric containing no charge and no conduction current, the field equations \cite{Jordan_book_95} become  
\begin{subequations}
\begin{eqnarray}\label{max_eqn_free}
\bigtriangledown\times \overrightarrow{H}&=&\frac{\partial \overrightarrow{D}}{\partial t}\label{me_1}\\
\bigtriangledown\times \overrightarrow{E}&=&-\frac{\partial \overrightarrow{B}}{\partial t}\label{me_2}\\
\bigtriangledown\cdot \overrightarrow{D}&=&0\label{me_3}\\
\bigtriangledown\cdot \overrightarrow{B}&=&0\label{me_4}
\end{eqnarray}
\end{subequations}
Substituting (\ref{Consti_rela_BH}) and (\ref{Consti_rela_DE}) into (\ref{me_1}) and (\ref{me_1}), the Maxwell\rq s curl equations become 
\begin{eqnarray}\label{Faraday_eqn2}
\mu\frac{\partial \overrightarrow{H}}{\partial t}=-\bigtriangledown\times \overrightarrow{E}
\end{eqnarray}
\begin{eqnarray}\label{Ampere_eqn2}
\varepsilon\frac{\partial \overrightarrow{E}}{\partial t}=\bigtriangledown\times \overrightarrow{H}
\end{eqnarray}
